With what information is available, I would suggest doing something like the following simplified version:

Container
```javascript
class Container extends Component {
  constructor(props) {
    super(props);
    this.state = {
      name: &#39;&#39;,
      other_value: &#39;&#39;,
    }
  }

  handleChange = (field, value) =&gt; {
    this.setState({ [field]: value });
  }

  valid = () =&gt; {
    if (!this.state.name) {
      return false;
    }
  }

  submit = () =&gt; {
    if (this.valid()) {
      // call your redux submit
    }
  }

  render() {
    return (
      &lt;MyForm
        values={this.state}
        handleChange={this.handleChange}
        submit={this.submit}
      /&gt;
    );
  }
}
```

Form component
```javascript
const MyForm = (props) =&gt; {
  return (
    &lt;form onSubmit={props.submit}&gt;
      &lt;TextField
        onChange={(e) =&gt; props.handleChange(&#39;name&#39;, e.target.value)}
        value={props.values.name}
        required
      /&gt;
      &lt;TextField
        onChange={(e) =&gt; props.handleChange(&#39;other_value&#39;, e.target.value)}
        value={props.values.other_value}
      /&gt;
      &lt;button type=&quot;submit&quot;&gt;Submit&lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;/form&gt;
  );
}
```


First, if you are using an `onChange` on your input, you should also provide its value to insure they remain in-sync.

Second, If you want the `required` prop to have an effect, you should make sure your submit function is called by the form. The `required` prop is just passed down to the `input` element which will get used by the wrapping `form` [(explanation of required)](https://www.w3schools.com/tags/att_input_required.asp). So if the form isn&#39;t the one calling your submit function, `required` will be ignored.

Lastly, I only provided a simple validate function, if you want it to be more comprehensive, just add more checks and return specific errors or an array of errors instead of a simple true or false. You could also skip the validation function completely if a simple required check is all you need.

